This Java code implements a directed weighted graph using an adjacency list representation. It defines a custom Edge class with dest (destination node) and weight attributes. 
The program first reads two integers n (number of nodes) and e (number of edges), then reads e directed edges as triples (u, v, w) representing a directed edge from node u to node v with weight w.
It creates an array of ArrayList<Edge> of size n+1 (index 0 unused), initializes each list, and adds the edge new Edge(v, w) only to adj[u] (no reverse edge, since the graph is directed). 
Finally, it prints the adjacency list for nodes 1 through n, displaying each edge with its destination node and weight.




import java.util.*;

class Edge {
    int dest;
    int weight;
    
    Edge(int dest, int weight){
        this.dest = dest;
        this.weight = weight;
    }
}

public class Main{
    public static void main(String[] args){
        Scanner sc = new Scanner(System.in);
        int n = sc.nextInt();
        int e = sc.nextInt();
        
        ArrayList<Edge>[] adj = new ArrayList[n+1];
        
        for(int i = 0; i<=n; i++){
            adj[i] = new ArrayList<>();
        }
        
        for(int i = 0; i<e; i++){
            int u = sc.nextInt();
            int v = sc.nextInt();
            int w = sc.nextInt();
            adj[u].add(new Edge(v, w));
        }
        for(int i = 0; i<n; i++){
            System.out.print(i+1 + ": ");
            for(Edge a : adj[i+1]){
                System.out.print("(" + a.dest + ", weight=" + a.weight + ") ");
            }
            System.out.print("\n");
        }
        sc.close();
    }
}
